We let the coordinate $R$ be the radius of the spherical cluster, the growth thereof is described as a motion along the $R$-axis. The growth takes place in discrete jumps of length $\lambda$, i.e the radius variation due to the addition of a particle.
Since all cluster sizes are discretely distributed, the allowed sizes define a set of nodes  along the $R$-axis at distance $\lambda$ from each other. Nodes can be labelled with a discrete index $n$ expressing the number of particles forming the nucleus $n$.
We call the probabilities of a jump to the right (particle addition to the cluster)  or to the left (particle loss),  $q_+(n)$ and $q_-(n)$, respectively. \\
